#Excercise 3:  Multiple regression model 

  #a) Fit the model    
  g <- lm(Price ~ KM + Weight+Tow_Bar, data=toyota)
  summary(g)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Price ~ KM + Weight + Tow_Bar, data = toyota)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -19077.1  -1248.8    -38.2   1230.7   8795.0 
## 
## Coefficients:
##               Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)
## (Intercept) -2.678e+04  1.168e+03 -22.930  < 2e-16
## KM          -5.288e-02  1.515e-03 -34.910  < 2e-16
## Weight       3.853e+01  1.079e+00  35.726  < 2e-16
## Tow_BarYes  -6.835e+02  1.271e+02  -5.378  8.8e-08
## 
## Residual standard error: 2144 on 1432 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.6513, Adjusted R-squared:  0.6505 
## F-statistic: 891.4 on 3 and 1432 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
  #b) Residual five-number summary


  #Inference: The "RESIDUAL" term represents the deviations of the observed values 
  #y(price) from their means which are normally distributed with mean 0 and variance 0. 
  #The five number summary for residual tells that median is -38.2 and the range of the residual
  # variable is -19077.1 to 8795.0. Interquartile range (q3-q1) of the variable is 2479.5.  
  
  # For Skewness
  skewness(g$fitted.values)
## [1] 1.548187
  #Inference: The Skewness is 1.55 which means that the function is positively skewed 
  # and is directly related to the independent variables. 
  
  #c) Interpret the estimated value the coefficient.
  coef(g)
##   (Intercept)            KM        Weight    Tow_BarYes 
## -2.677787e+04 -5.288276e-02  3.853090e+01 -6.835050e+02
  #Inference: Intercept is -2.68. The linear model is intercepting y-axis 
  # at -2.68 with the input value, KM = -5.29 , Weight = 3.85 and Tow_Bar = -6.83. 
  #The complete data can be fitted into a linear model with : 
  #price = -2.68 - 5.29*KM + 3.85*Weight -6.83*Tow_Bar
 
  #d) The signs of slope coefficients is negative for KM and Tow_bar while
  #positive for weight. The output function y is inversely proportional to 
  #km hence the negative slope. For larger the weight,
  #more will be the price. Also, tow_bar is having negative slope with the dependent  (price) variable. 
  #which means that if a car has tow_bar then the price of the car decreases.
  #e) The price of car decreases with more number of KM . For every increase in price of 5.28
  #the km travelled is reduced by a single unit.
  
  #f) The price of car increases with increase in weight. The price gets increased by 3.85 units when the 
  # weight is increased by single unit.
  
  #g) For finding the price difference between "Yes"and "No" factor of Towbar, with same 
  # same km and weight,we'll use the coef function b/w price and tow_Bar . 
  g2 <- lm(Price ~Tow_Bar, data=toyota)
  coef(g2)
## (Intercept)  Tow_BarYes 
##   11118.481   -1395.175
  g3 <- lm (Price ~Tow_Bar, data=toyota)
  # The price value obtained for "Yes" is 11118.481
  
  #h) The Coefficient of Determination, Multiple R square is .6513.
  #Inference: Since the R square of 1 indicates a perfectly fitting data
  # we can conclude that multiple R square of .6513 would be a good fit
  # to the given linear regression model. 
  
#___________________________________________________________________
#Excercise 4: Goodness of Fit
#a)  Get R2 using fitted values
  
  cor(g$fitted.values,toyota$Price)
## [1] 0.8070117
  Deviance <- deviance(g)
  Deviance
## [1] 6583099567
  d <- toyota$Price
  TotalSS <- sum((d-mean(d))^2) 
  TotalSS
## [1] 18877241464
  Deviance/TotalSS
## [1] 0.3487321
  1 - Deviance/TotalSS 
## [1] 0.6512679
  #Inference1: Cor is .80701  which is also called R. After squaring the value of R
  # we get R square is equal to (.8071 * .8071) = .6514 which we observed
  # in multiple r square value.
  #Inference2: The R Square is also calculated by deviance function.
  # we can calculate r square by 1- ( Deviance/TotalSS) where totalSS is sum of squares. 
  
# b) Fit Plot  

  library(ggplot2)
  qplot(g$fitted.values, Price, data=toyota) +
  
  #Graph with 45 degree angle (Slope=1)  
  geom_abline(intercept=-2.78, slope=1)

  #Inference: Fitted values from the given linear model with variable KM, Weight , Tow_Bar 
  #to predict the actual prices well.
